GRAPHIC DEVICE INTERFACES
Graphic device interfaces connect displays (monitors, projectors, TVs) to computers and other output sources. 
These interfaces can carry "video signals" — and in many cases, "audio too".

1.VGA (Video Graphics Array)
| Feature          | Description                                    |
|------------------|------------------------------------------------|
| 🔌 Type           | Analog                                         |
| 📺 Use            | Older monitors and projectors                 |
| 📏 Pins           | 15-pin D-sub connector (blue)                 |
| 🎵 Audio Support  | ❌ No                                          |
| 📉 Max Res        | Up to 1080p (but analog quality)              |

#Analog means the signal is sent as a continuous electrical wave rather than as binary digital data (0s and 1s).


2.HDMI (High-Definition Multimedia Interface)
| Feature          | Description                                    |
|------------------|------------------------------------------------|
| 🔌 Type           | Digital                                        |
| 📺 Use            | Modern TVs, monitors, gaming consoles         |
| 🎵 Audio Support  | ✅ Yes (video + audio in one cable)           |
| 📹 Max Res        | Up to 8K with HDMI 2.1                         |
| 🎮 Extra Use      | Supports CEC (remote control), Ethernet       |

> Most common home and multimedia display connection.

3.DVI(Digital Visual Interface)
| Feature          | Description                                    |
|------------------|------------------------------------------------|
| 🔌 Type           | Digital or Analog                              |
| 📺 Use            | Older monitors and PCs                        |
| 🎵 Audio Support  | ❌ No (video only)                            |
| 📷 Variants       | DVI-D (Digital), DVI-A (Analog), DVI-I (Both) |
| 📹 Max Res        | Up to 1920x1200 (single link) or 2560x1600 (dual) |

 Looks chunky& white & bigger than VGA/HDMI; not used in newer devices.
 DVI gives good digital video.


4.DisplayPort
| Feature          | Description                                    |
|------------------|------------------------------------------------|
| 🔌 Type           | Digital                                        |
| 📺 Use            | High-end monitors, PCs                        |
| 🎵 Audio Support  | ✅ Yes                                         |
| ⚡ Max Res        | Up to 8K (with version 2.0)                    |
| 🔁 Other Use      | Can carry USB and other signals (like USB-C)  |
Preferred for high refresh rate gaming and pro displays.
It allows high resolution - High resolution refers to the number of pixels on the screen.
The more pixels = sharper and clearer the image.

